				<p><p>This is a great question and has come up a couple of times already (see <a href="https://robotics.stackexchange.com/questions/712/quadruped-learning-simulator">Quadruped Learning Simulator</a> and See <a href="https://robotics.stackexchange.com/questions/697/standalone-or-capable-of-being-robotics-simulator">Standalone (or capable of being) Robotics Simulator</a>).</p>

<p>In short, the de facto standard simulators for all things robotic are <a href="http://playerstage.sourceforge.net/" rel="nofollow noreferrer">Stage</a> (for 2D) and <a href="http://gazebosim.org/" rel="nofollow noreferrer">Gazebo</a> (for 3D). <a href="http://www.ros.org/wiki/" rel="nofollow noreferrer">ROS</a> is another option for what you are trying to do. Not only because it is highly compatible with the aforementioned simulators but because it has it's own simple visualization tool called <a href="http://www.ros.org/wiki/rviz" rel="nofollow noreferrer">RViz</a> which excels at displaying primitives as you describe.</p>
